03612nam a22005295i 9780300159134DE-B159720230529094047.0m|||||o||d||||||||cr || ||||||||230529t20122012ctu    fo  d z      eng d  a97803001591347 a10.12987/97803001591342doi  a(DE-B1597)485837  a(OCoLC)817540015  aDE-B1597bengcDE-B1597erda0 aeng  actucUS-CT 7aREL1060002bisacsh04a294.3/3651 aLopez, Donald S., eauthor.4aut4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/aut14aThe Scientific Buddha :bHis Short and Happy Life /cDonald S. Lopez. 1aNew Haven, CT : bYale University Press, c[2012] 4cÂ©2012  a1 online resource (160 p.)  atextbtxt2rdacontent  acomputerbc2rdamedia  aonline resourcebcr2rdacarrier  atext filebPDF2rda0 aThe Terry Lectures Series00tFrontmatter -- tContents -- tPreface -- tAcknowledgments -- tONE. A Purified Religion -- tTWO. The Birth of the Scientific Buddha -- tTHREE. The Problem with Karma -- tINTERLUDE. A Primer on Buddhist Meditation -- tFOUR. The Death of the Scientific Buddha -- tNotes -- tIndex0 arestricted accessuhttp://purl.org/coar/access_right/c_16ecfonline access with authorization2star  aThis book tells the story of the Scientific Buddha, "born" in Europe in the 1800s but commonly confused with the Buddha born in India 2,500 years ago. The Scientific Buddha was sent into battle against Christian missionaries, who were proclaiming across Asia that Buddhism was a form of superstition. He proved the missionaries wrong, teaching a dharma that was in harmony with modern science. And his influence continues. Today his teaching of "mindfulness" is heralded as the cure for all manner of maladies, from depression to high blood pressure.In this potent critique, a well-known chronicler of the West's encounter with Buddhism demonstrates how the Scientific Buddha's teachings deviate in crucial ways from those of the far older Buddha of ancient India. Donald Lopez shows that the Western focus on the Scientific Buddha threatens to bleach Buddhism of its vibrancy, complexity, and power, even as the superficial focus on "mindfulness" turns Buddhism into merely the latest self-help movement. The Scientific Buddha has served his purpose, Lopez argues. It is now time for him to pass into nirvana. This is not to say, however, that the teachings of the ancient Buddha must be dismissed as mere cultural artifacts. They continue to present a potent challenge, even to our modern world.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 29. Mai 2023) 7aRELIGION / Religion & Science.2bisacsh08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertYale University Press Backlist eBook-Package 2000-2013z97831105379940 cprintz978030015912740uhttps://doi.org/10.12987/978030015913440uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9780300159134423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/document/cover/isbn/9780300159134/original  a978-3-11-053799-4  Yale University Press Backlist eBook-Package 2000-2013c2000d2013  aEBA_FAO  aEBA_UCA_YUP  aGBV-deGruyter-alles  aZDB-23-UCY